  "text": "incidence of cough; 2=smooth extubation, slight coughing (1~2 coughs); 3=moderate coughing (3~4 coughs); 4=severe or repetitive coughing (5~10 coughs); 5=patient discomfort, poor extubation (>10 severe coughs) [CITATION_1] . 7. BCS were assessed at T4 (10 min after extubation). BCS: 0=continuous pain; 1=no pain without movement, but serious pain when breathing deeply or coughing; 2=no pain without movement, but mild pain when breathing deeply or coughing; 3=no pain, even when breathing deeply; and 4=no pain when coughing) [CITATION_2] . 8. Potential adverse drug reactions were noted during PACU: bradycardia (HR <50 bpm), tachycardia (HR >100 bpm), hypotension [mean arterial pressure (MAP) was less than 30% of the baseline], hypertension (MAP was more than 30% of the baseline), respiratory depression (respiratory rate £8 bpm or SpO2 £90% for a duration exceeding 5 min), glossoptosis, nausea or vomiting, rigors, and bleeding.",
